data.title: New film reveals the tragic life of Hollywood's Cary Grant
data.meta_description: The upcoming Showtime documentary Becoming Cary Grant, explores how the dashingly handsome Hollywood star's troubled past affected his relationships with women.
data.text:
He's arguable Hollywood's greatest ever leading man, dashingly handsome, suave and sophisticated. But movie star Cary Grant was desperately insecure, destroying his marriages and multiple love affairs to compensate for his unhappy childhood, an upcoming documentary reveals.

'Becoming Cary Grant,' that will air on Showtime beginning June 9 explores how one of Tinsel Town's legendary stars was haunted by the absence of his mother and the troubled past he left behind.

'I was surrounded by all sorts of attractive girls,' the debonair star reveals in the new film, 'I was never able to form attachments. If I had paid more attention I might have found contentment in marriage.'

The British-born actor grew up in abject poverty, the only surviving child of an alcoholic father and over-protective mother with mental health issues.

He was 11 when his mother Elsie vanished, supposedly to a seaside resort, and his father Elias moved across Britain to start a new family with another women.

Scroll down for video

Grant, born Archibald Leach in the British shipping port of Bristol, joined a vaudeville troupe and took off for America.

It would be another 20 years before the Hollywood heartthrob discovered his mother was alive  placed in the Bristol Lunatic Asylum on his father's say so.

Five-times married, Grant's tragic childhood and troubles with women are recounted in the film which will premier at the Cannes Film Festival May 23.

The documentary makers use Grant's own words  spoken by 'Wolf Hall' and 'Game of Thrones' actor Jonathan Pryce  to tell the 'Affair To Remember' star's painful rags to riches story.

Grant's recently discovered unpublished memoir, letters from his mother and never-before-seen home movie clips help tell the tragic tale.

Recounting his parents, he says: 'Father was a tallish, handsome man with a fancy mustache. My mother was a delicate, dark-haired beauty.'

Talking of his older brother John, who died before he was born, Grant says his mother 'closed the door on his thumb. He developed gangrene and died. She never forgave herself.

'My mother tried to smother me in care, she was over protective. She kept me in baby dresses. For a while I wasn't sure if I was a boy or a girl.

'My father pressed suits in a clothing factory. He progressed too slowly for my mother's dreams.

'The relationship between my mother and father grew unhappier.

'I came home from school one day and she was gone. My cousins told me she had gone to a seaside resort. I thought that odd. It seemed rather unusual but I accepted it was one of those things that adults do.

'I regularly haunted the Bristol wharfs and sat alone and contemplated.

'It gradually dawned on me that she was not coming back. She left a void in my life, a sadness of spirit that affected everything I did. I always felt my mother rejected me.'

He found comfort in vaudeville theater  possibly as a way of fantasizing about a happier life. And by 16 he found his way to America, making money standing on stilts and wearing a giant sandwich board to advertise New York's Coney Island attractions.

His good looks helped make him a Broadway leading man and it wasn't long before he caught the attention of Hollywood, where he quickly made a name for himself in the early 1930s in screwball romantic comedies.

He changed his name to the more American-sounding Cary Grant but his insecurities were never far from the surface. Considered 'jewelry' on the arm of Hollywood's leading beauties, his personal life was a mess.

As one of his many lovers said later, Grant 'did not know how to give affection and did not know how to receive it.'

He was already a box office success when he eloped with actress Virginia Cherrill  something he would do with two more wives. She left him after seven months alleging he was abusive.

And as he concedes in 'Becoming Cary Grant, the union was doomed from the start.

'I doubt if either of us was relaxed enough to trust what we had,' he said.

'My possessiveness and fear of losing her bought about the very thing I had feared, the loss of her.'

Virginia had slapped him with divorce papers when word came from Britain that his hard-drinking father was ill.

'Father died in 1935 of liver disease. My old life at the time of his death was following a similar pattern,' Grant says, in the documentary.

It is unclear if his father made a death-bed confession about his mother's whereabouts  the emotionally-stunted Grant rarely discussed his old life with his wives or close friends.

But having discovered her whereabouts, he set about making things right, getting her out of the institution and into a nursing home.

Later she wrote him gushing letters  addressed to Mr A. A. Leach at Paramount Studios -- calling him 'my darling' and telling him how proud she was. He signed his letters to her using his old name Archie.

But he kept her at arms-length and there was never a suggestion of moving her to America, despite Elsie saying in letters that she wished they lived closer.

And Grant's friends who met Elsie recalled that she showed him no affection when they met, barely giving him a peck on the cheek.

The documentary also reveals Elsie's medical records, noting how her husband had told staff at the Bristol Lunatic Asylum she had been 'queer in her head for some months.

'She thinks she's being poisoned, hears voices and thinks she is being watched.'

Even though she was not considered 'a danger to others or herself,' it was enough to have her committed for 20 years on the say so of a philandering husband, who almost instantly started a new family.

The discovery, at the age of 31, threw Grant into turmoil but it took him another 20 years  and 100 experimental LSD trips to 'open' his mind  to even try to understand what had happened, the film revealed.

In the meantime he continued to make the same mistakes, hurting the women who loved him.

Wife number two was 'poor little rich girl' Barbara Hutton, the Woolworth's heiress worth $50 million. Nicknamed 'Cash and Carry' by Hollywood gossips, the couple had absolutely nothing in common.

She hated Hollywood and wanted to socialize with her own friends. He made five movies during their three-year marriage and preferred reading film scripts in bed to going out.

'I doubt I ever understood Barbara,' Grant says in the documentary. 'Our backgrounds, culture, were completely unalike.'

He met wife number three, actress Betsy Drake, on a ship sailing back from Europe and quickly became besotted. She was 19 years younger and reluctant to get involved with such a huge star.

'Betsy was good for me, she educated me to better myself, she patiently led me to better literature, to self discovery,' Grant says in the documentary.

Those lessons ultimately led to them both experimenting with LSD and Grant says: 'She gradually provoked my interest, just as she probably intended.

'The first breakthrough came when I realized I was the one who repeated the same mistakes and patterns.

'It was like a light finally went off in my brain. I finally realized all the pain I thought my mother had given me. Now that I know I hurt the very women I loved.

'After weeks of treatment came the day when I saw the light. When I broke through, I felt a cleansing of my fears and guilt.

'It was a wasting of so many years. The shock of each revelation brings with it an anguish of sadness for what was not known before in the wasted years of ignorance and, at the same time, an ecstasy of joy at being freed from the shackles of such ignorance.

'I lost all the tension I have been crippling myself with, a wasting of so many years.

'Now everything changed, my attitude towards woman has changed. At last I am close to happiness.'

Grant had more than 100 LSD sessions  spending the better part of one day a week on acid trips administered by his own personal Dr Feelgood, Mortimer Hartman.

'During my LSD therapy I learned a great deal and the result of it all was a rebirth. Not completely because you cut back the barnacles to find barnacles,' he says.

'In the end, there is no end to getting well. [But] LSD made me realize I was killing my mother through my relationships with other women.

'I made the mistake of thinking that each one of my wives was my mother.

'Once I realized you have all things inside you, love and hate, then you can use love to get rid of hate.

'The moment you realize this is a wrench. You feel the whole top of your head lifting off.'

His 13-year marriage to Betsy was his longest but acid trips couldn't save their damaged relationship. They split in 1962 and three years later he tied the knot for the fourth time with actress Dyan Cannon, who was 33 years his junior.

The marriage lasted just three years but produced what Grant considered to be his greatest production  his only child Jennifer.

Grant was 62 when he effectively retired from Hollywood and set about giving Jennifer the happy childhood he never had.

Photographs and his own home movies  many seen for the same time courtesy of 51-year-old actress Jennifer  reveal a doting dad who enjoyed nothing more than spending time with his beloved daughter.

Jennifer also reveals a different side of her father in the documentary, explaining how people assumed the suave, confident actor was the same off screen.

'One can imagine we were at parties and premieres, things like that,' she says.

'But really we were at home watching television, he loved television, or playing backgammon or cards.'

And somewhat tellingly, considering his insecurities, Jennifer says: 'He was incredibly protective of me as his only child, his little girl. He had fears about the male population and how they would react to me.

'He didn't like me going out late. At first he would be angry at me, then the silent treatment if I didn't obey his rules. But he was worried and I knew it.'

His fifth and final marriage was to British hotel PR agent Barbara Harris, who also speaks at the end of the 89-minute documentary.

She was 47 years his junior and Grant was still suffering from commitment issues when they met.

'He was a little bit shy, anxious, wanting to make sure I was the right person,' she says.

'He was a little bit weary of women. Somewhere in the depths of his mind was the fact that women were not always going to be there.'

She worked hard to convince him she would stand by him, saying they married 'once he realized I was totally in his life and I loved him.'

Attempting to sum up her husband's persona, she adds: 'Cary was a strange combination of someone who used to be him and who he had become and still a bit of the old Archie Leach.'

Even Grant, who died in 1986, aged 82, seemed unsure of who he really was and how to deal with his emotions.

'Most women are instinctively wiser and emotionally mature than men,' he says towards the end of the documentary, while talking about his 'To Catch A Thief' co-star Grace Kelly.

The documentary uses Grant's films and especially his relationship with director Alfred Hitchcock, another working-class Brit who went to Hollywood and reinvented himself, to reveal his vulnerability.

In the 1946 film Notorious, he appears emotionally damaged and unreachable, resentful of the woman he loves. And in North By Northwest  one of his most famous movies  he reveals the commitment phobia that dogged him his entire life.

Yet it was an earlier 1944 film None But The Lonely Heart  where he plays a down-at-heel Londoner returning to his difficult mother  that he tellingly reveals his own family dynamics.

Grant insisted RKO Pictures buy the rights to Richard Llewllyn's dark novel. Ethel Barrymore plays his ungrateful mother and in abusive scenes between them a photograph of Grant's real-life father is seen on the wall.

In the documentary, Grant admits that turning his back on his old life and reinventing himself as a suave, sophisticated heartthrob, did not make him happy.

'Little did I know I would still be seeking serenity 30 years later,' he says.

'I don't know what I have learned about love. It took a long time for me to even try to understand love.'
